Because there is no such thing. Colonialism is violent, never good. There is no benign colonialist. #ThorRagnarok
This claim of a distinction between the two actually opens up the space in which "good colonialism" operates. That's what's been eating away at me for ages. #ThorRagnarok
The possible power of those overlapped murals showing how two aspects of violent coloniser and benign family person coexisting is subverted through that narrative choice. #ThorRagnarok
THIS. This is what pisses me off—that implication of a benign, respected colonial imperial rule on Odin's part which retains this even in death. #ThorRagnarok
We're meant to see Odin as the better of two violent colonial forces because he stopped at nine worlds versus Hela who wanted more. But THEY'RE BOTH VIOLENT COLONISTS??? #ThorRagnarok

Not kidding: but the idea that the old colonial order gets to pass away, respected as a benign father who returns to give his successor strength actively pisses me off. #ThorRagnarok

Which has been eating away at me because that outer mural destruction paralleled the death of Odin and BOTH got to keep the assumptions of "goodness." It wasn't presented as two halves of the same coin! #ThorRagnarok

And yes, they did co-exist one upon the other, and this is how violent colonialism works, but the destruction of the outer, newer mural implies that we are now seeing the seeming truth of things. #ThorRagnarok

It was because they seemed to indicate two separate world views: one of violent conquest and the other of benign ruling and loving family, the implication being that these couldn't be present at the same time. #ThorRagnarok
